Dialogue: 0,0:48:02.64,0:48:09.28,Default,,0,0,0,,innocence, the innocence of the child\Nthen is man's Achilles heel. On the one
Dialogue: 0,0:48:09.28,0:48:15.28,Default,,0,0,0,,hand, it leads him into great\Nmagnificent evolution. On the other
Dialogue: 0,0:48:15.28,0:48:20.72,Default,,0,0,0,,hand, it can lead him downhill.\NYes.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:20.72,0:48:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,H\Nthis was noted by the famous philosopher
Dialogue: 0,0:48:28.00,0:48:35.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Decart who talked about the rest\Ninternal and rest external. Externa rest
Dialogue: 0,0:48:35.28,0:48:40.80,Default,,0,0,0,,interna is\Nuh how you see the world. That's
Dialogue: 0,0:48:40.80,0:48:45.20,Default,,0,0,0,,perception.\NRest interna is that capacity.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:45.20,0:48:50.72,Default,,0,0,0,,You look at the world and this is the\Nway the world looks rest internally.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:50.72,0:48:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,This is in contrast. We'll make the same\Ncomparison when we get to Socrates
Dialogue: 0,0:48:56.00,0:49:03.92,Default,,0,0,0,,with rest externa. That rest externa\Nmeans the reality of that which is as it
Dialogue: 0,0:49:03.92,0:49:09.44,Default,,0,0,0,,is not as you perceive it not what you\Nthink of or feel about it. Though
Dialogue: 0,0:49:09.44,0:49:15.92,Default,,0,0,0,,independent of our intelligence and our\Nwitnessing, there is an infinite reality
Dialogue: 0,0:49:15.92,0:49:19.35,Default,,0,0,0,,which is not dependent on our\Nobservation.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:19.35,0:49:25.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Although some theorists of quantum\Nmechanics such as mindful universe would
Dialogue: 0,0:49:25.28,0:49:30.31,Default,,0,0,0,,declare that there would be no universe\Nwithout consciousness. Without
Dialogue: 0,0:49:30.31,0:49:38.31,Default,,0,0,0,,consciousness, no universe is possible.\Nuh but for practical reasons. Then we
Dialogue: 0,0:49:38.31,0:49:45.04,Default,,0,0,0,,remind oursel of Socrates dictim as\Nwell. Socrates says manu uh always
Dialogue: 0,0:49:45.04,0:49:51.44,Default,,0,0,0,,chooses the good. Socrates says man\Nchooses the good always. It's just that
Dialogue: 0,0:49:51.44,0:49:55.76,Default,,0,0,0,,he doesn't know what the real good is.\NHe doesn't know the real good from the
Dialogue: 0,0:49:55.76,0:50:01.04,Default,,0,0,0,,illusory good. So if he thinks wealth\Nand fame and happiness and having your
Dialogue: 0,0:50:01.04,0:50:06.31,Default,,0,0,0,,blouse flop open on international\Ntelevision is good, it will happen. You
Dialogue: 0,0:50:06.31,0:50:10.40,Default,,0,0,0,,see\Nand make your career. On the other hand,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:10.40,0:50:17.52,Default,,0,0,0,,if you think it's a disaster. So whether\Nit's good or bad, then so because man
Dialogue: 0,0:50:17.52,0:50:24.07,Default,,0,0,0,,cannot discern the good from the false,\Nhe projects goodness onto the things
Dialogue: 0,0:50:24.07,0:50:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that he desires.\NSo the attraction of thing that you see
Dialogue: 0,0:50:30.00,0:50:34.48,Default,,0,0,0,,of course which is the whole essence\Nalso of the book glamour which I
Dialogue: 0,0:50:34.48,0:50:40.96,Default,,0,0,0,,mentioned many times\Nuh man projects this aura of
Dialogue: 0,0:50:40.96,0:50:47.68,Default,,0,0,0,,desiraability upon the external world\Nand thinks that it is the thing itself
Dialogue: 0,0:50:47.68,0:50:54.88,Default,,0,0,0,,that he desires whereas actually it's\Nit's the magnification the exaggeration
Dialogue: 0,0:50:54.88,0:50:59.52,Default,,0,0,0,,uh that is the glamour that is\Nprojected. And what she points out in
Dialogue: 0,0:50:59.52,0:51:05.20,Default,,0,0,0,,her famous book is of course that\Nglamour is an actual energy. Let's just
Dialogue: 0,0:51:05.20,0:51:11.76,Default,,0,0,0,,reaffirm that. We have permission to ask\Nabout this. Uh glamour is an actual
Dialogue: 0,0:51:11.76,0:51:18.64,Default,,0,0,0,,energy.\NIt's an actual energy that we project.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:18.64,0:51:24.24,Default,,0,0,0,,So we can stop finding fault with the\Nworld and say because I I wanted that
Dialogue: 0,0:51:24.24,0:51:30.40,Default,,0,0,0,,car or I wanted that position, I wanted\Nit. It's because I projected specialness
Dialogue: 0,0:51:30.40,0:51:35.04,Default,,0,0,0,,onto it. And of course the course of\Nmiracles is also based on
Dialogue: 0,0:51:35.04,0:51:40.55,Default,,0,0,0,,differentiating the specialness that we\Nproject onto things from the their inner
Dialogue: 0,0:51:40.55,0:51:48.80,Default,,0,0,0,,reality. We project the specialness.\NSo Socrates dictum is extremely useful
Dialogue: 0,0:51:48.80,0:51:55.35,Default,,0,0,0,,in because it again reminds you of the\Ninnocence of man because man's
Dialogue: 0,0:51:55.35,0:51:59.92,Default,,0,0,0,,consciousness is not sufficiently aware.\NIt doesn't even know that it's
Dialogue: 0,0:51:59.92,0:52:06.64,Default,,0,0,0,,projecting specialness, uniqueness and\Ndesiraability onto the external world.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:06.64,0:52:11.11,Default,,0,0,0,,And by commonality of opinion then it's\Njust concluded that that's a social
Dialogue: 0,0:52:11.11,0:52:19.59,Default,,0,0,0,,reality that everybody wants to be rich\Nfamous and drive the latest uh whatever
Dialogue: 0,0:52:19.59,0:52:23.35,Default,,0,0,0,,mini car. What's a little car we saw in\NParis?
Dialogue: 0,0:52:23.35,0:52:27.92,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Um smart car.\N>> Smart car. I think the most prestigious
Dialogue: 0,0:52:27.92,0:52:33.11,Default,,0,0,0,,car now is a smart car.\NAnd we were disappointed you couldn't
Dialogue: 0,0:52:33.11,0:52:37.44,Default,,0,0,0,,buy one when we got to the states and\Nthey wouldn't license them because they
Dialogue: 0,0:52:37.44,0:52:42.96,Default,,0,0,0,,didn't have\Nrequires safety safeguards etc. But in
Dialogue: 0,0:52:42.96,0:52:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Europe everywhere you go there's this\Nsmart car and of course only takes about
Dialogue: 0,0:52:46.72,0:52:54.16,Default,,0,0,0,,this long to park it and really was\Nhelped solve the gasoline price oil
Dialogue: 0,0:52:54.16,0:53:01.35,Default,,0,0,0,,problem.\NUh so the this narcissism then creates a
Dialogue: 0,0:53:01.35,0:53:04.80,Default,,0,0,0,,disturbance the disturbance of\Nnarcissism
Dialogue: 0,0:53:04.80,0:53:10.31,Default,,0,0,0,,a distortion\Nbecause we're inflated about a certain
Dialogue: 0,0:53:10.31,0:53:17.52,Default,,0,0,0,,we're inflated about a certain value\Nthen we think that it exists out in the
Dialogue: 0,0:53:17.52,0:53:23.76,Default,,0,0,0,,world and it's only our own narcissism.\NYou know being a multi-millionaire was
Dialogue: 0,0:53:23.76,0:53:28.80,Default,,0,0,0,,will guarantee to make you happy,\Nfamous, wealthy and etc.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:28.80,0:53:32.80,Default,,0,0,0,,But discernment then begins to discern\Nthe opening of the third eye of the
Dialogue: 0,0:53:32.80,0:53:38.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Buddha body. You now begin to see the\Nessence of things rather than their
Dialogue: 0,0:53:38.07,0:53:42.88,Default,,0,0,0,,appearance. That it isn't the money that\Nmakes you happy. It's what you do with
Dialogue: 0,0:53:42.88,0:53:48.48,Default,,0,0,0,,it, what it means to you. And whether\Nyou use it for out of love of others or
Dialogue: 0,0:53:48.48,0:53:54.24,Default,,0,0,0,,out of greed for in for sensation and\Npossession. Yes. And here's a very
Dialogue: 0,0:53:54.24,0:53:57.76,Default,,0,0,0,,important\Num thing I wrote at the last minute
Dialogue: 0,0:53:57.76,0:54:01.92,Default,,0,0,0,,which is un unreadable. What does it\Nsay?
Dialogue: 0,0:54:01.92,0:54:08.24,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Doubt and discernment versus\Ngullibility.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:08.24,0:54:14.40,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Gullibility. Oh, gullibility.\NGullibility. Yes. Well, um, so the
Dialogue: 0,0:54:14.40,0:54:21.76,Default,,0,0,0,,innocence of the child, uh, everyone is\Ngullible to a certain degree and and
Dialogue: 0,0:54:21.76,0:54:26.64,Default,,0,0,0,,they become more gullible. You hold the\Nidea that you're not gullible, which
Dialogue: 0,0:54:26.64,0:54:30.24,Default,,0,0,0,,proves that you're quite gullible\Nbecause anybody who's not gullible
Dialogue: 0,0:54:30.24,0:54:34.16,Default,,0,0,0,,wouldn't believe they're not gullible\Nbecause everybody's gullible.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:34.16,0:54:40.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Why? Because the programming is not\Nconscious. The programming is automated
Dialogue: 0,0:54:40.40,0:54:45.44,Default,,0,0,0,,and it's designed\Nhandily crafted. Uh, everybody in this
Dialogue: 0,0:54:45.44,0:54:52.07,Default,,0,0,0,,audience has been programmed. Let's go\Nin for paranoia today. Every everybody
Dialogue: 0,0:54:52.07,0:54:56.40,Default,,0,0,0,,in this audience has been programmed.\NResist.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:56.40,0:55:02.80,Default,,0,0,0,,So, you begin with facing that fact. In\Nwhat way might I be uh walking around
Dialogue: 0,0:55:02.80,0:55:07.59,Default,,0,0,0,,under an illusion? And what kind of\Nillusion could that be?
Dialogue: 0,0:55:07.59,0:55:12.31,Default,,0,0,0,,uh\Nso trying to transcend the illusions by
Dialogue: 0,0:55:12.31,0:55:19.44,Default,,0,0,0,,which people live and the glamours\Nassociated with them. Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:19.44,0:55:25.11,Default,,0,0,0,,The only way to transcend it is actually\Nby spiritual evolution.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:25.11,0:55:29.68,Default,,0,0,0,,the way out of mankind's dilemma. How to\Ntell truth from falsehood, how to not
Dialogue: 0,0:55:29.68,0:55:34.48,Default,,0,0,0,,get programmed, how to realize when you\Nare programmed, how to not sacrifice
Dialogue: 0,0:55:34.48,0:55:40.55,Default,,0,0,0,,your life for\Nsuperficial appearance.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:40.55,0:55:47.83,Default,,0,0,0,,The only way out of it is uh spiritual\Nevolution. And therefore
Dialogue: 0,0:55:47.83,0:55:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,uh the hope of mankind really rests on\Nthe spiritually evolved persons in the
Dialogue: 0,0:55:54.00,0:56:00.64,Default,,0,0,0,,in the uh population. Now we saw by that\Nbalance scale that spiritually evolved
Dialogue: 0,0:56:00.64,0:56:08.07,Default,,0,0,0,,people are extremely in the minority.\NThey're less than 3%. Yes, this is
Dialogue: 0,0:56:08.07,0:56:12.40,Default,,0,0,0,,significantly spiritually evolved.\NThey're less than 3%. They're less than
Dialogue: 0,0:56:12.40,0:56:17.04,Default,,0,0,0,,2%.\NThey're less than 3%. Okay, so less than
Dialogue: 0,0:56:17.04,0:56:21.44,Default,,0,0,0,,3%.\NSo the world's evolution and survival
Dialogue: 0,0:56:21.44,0:56:25.52,Default,,0,0,0,,depends actually on 3% of the\Npopulation.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:25.52,0:56:41.11,Default,,0,0,0,,All of whom most of whom are here today.\NThat seems comical,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:41.11,0:56:46.88,Default,,0,0,0,,but um\Nthe people in this room here
Dialogue: 0,0:56:46.88,0:56:53.11,Default,,0,0,0,,counterbalance multi-millions\Nof less evolved humans.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:53.11,0:56:58.07,Default,,0,0,0,,This this group here today\Ncounterbalances multi-millions of other
Dialogue: 0,0:56:58.07,0:57:01.83,Default,,0,0,0,,humans.\NSo
Dialogue: 0,0:57:01.83,0:57:06.55,Default,,0,0,0,,that way you take your presence here\Nseriously and say
Dialogue: 0,0:57:06.55,0:57:11.59,Default,,0,0,0,,what you do is not just for your own\Nbenefit but it is helpful to all of
Dialogue: 0,0:57:11.59,0:57:16.96,Default,,0,0,0,,mankind because of the collective\Nconsciousness of mankind
Dialogue: 0,0:57:16.96,0:57:22.40,Default,,0,0,0,,as each person's condolini energy rises\Nand they just just from by becoming
Dialogue: 0,0:57:22.40,0:57:27.92,Default,,0,0,0,,spiritually committed you don't have to\Nbecome a Buddha to affect the world
Dialogue: 0,0:57:27.92,0:57:34.07,Default,,0,0,0,,to be spiritually committed\Nis already profoundly impacts the world
Dialogue: 0,0:57:34.07,0:57:40.16,Default,,0,0,0,,because the energy is so high it\Ncounterbalances many many thousands of
Dialogue: 0,0:57:40.16,0:57:45.52,Default,,0,0,0,,people who are not spiritually oriented.\NSo we serve
Dialogue: 0,0:57:45.52,0:57:50.88,Default,,0,0,0,,unwittingly\Njust by being what we are.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:50.88,0:57:55.76,Default,,0,0,0,,And I always say it's not what you do\Nthat changes the world. It's what you
Dialogue: 0,0:57:55.76,0:58:02.16,Default,,0,0,0,,are, what you have become.\NThat which you are by virtue of what you
Dialogue: 0,0:58:02.16,0:58:07.92,Default,,0,0,0,,are as you walk through the woods\Naffects all living things. Every tree,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:07.92,0:58:16.96,Default,,0,0,0,,every shrub, yes, is is aware. Every\Ntree, every shrub is aware when it
Dialogue: 0,0:58:16.96,0:58:23.35,Default,,0,0,0,,is in the presence of divinity. Resist.\NAha. Here you thought nature was
Dialogue: 0,0:58:23.35,0:58:28.55,Default,,0,0,0,,unconscious.\NNature, the tree knows
Dialogue: 0,0:58:28.55,0:58:34.88,Default,,0,0,0,,that which is in its presence. It\Nwitnesses the presence of God. The tree
Dialogue: 0,0:58:34.88,0:58:39.83,Default,,0,0,0,,witnesses the presence of God. Yes,\Nlet's say that the tree is the witness
Dialogue: 0,0:58:39.83,0:58:47.83,Default,,0,0,0,,to the presence of God by the ver oh by\Nvirtue as an innate virtue and as the
Dialogue: 0,0:58:47.83,0:58:51.76,Default,,0,0,0,,essence of life itself.\NAha.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:51.76,0:58:56.55,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, it is life itself that\Ngrants this virtue.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:56.55,0:59:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Not being holier than other people.\NAlthough we are a little holier,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:03.52,0:59:13.20,Default,,0,0,0,,we can be humble when we say we're\Nreally better than other people.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:13.20,0:59:20.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that is spoken out of humility\Nbecause it's a fact.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:20.72,0:59:25.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So, one part of spiritual evolution is\Nyou give up false humility. False
Dialogue: 0,0:59:25.20,0:59:30.72,Default,,0,0,0,,humility.\Nfalse humility
Dialogue: 0,0:59:30.72,0:59:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,and you own your birthright as a human\Nthat you inherit also an awareness which
Dialogue: 0,0:59:39.44,0:59:45.20,Default,,0,0,0,,is shared by divinity.\NIt's the divinity within you. It's the
Dialogue: 0,0:59:45.20,0:59:52.64,Default,,0,0,0,,divinity within nature. The tree is\Naware that you are passing by.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:52.64,1:00:01.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn't that amazing?\NThat's why I like kissing trees
Dialogue: 0,1:00:01.76,1:00:05.59,Default,,0,0,0,,north of San Francisco. Those wonderful\N>> tree huggers.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:05.59,1:00:10.79,Default,,0,0,0,,>> No, those wonderful that forest, huh?\NThe redwood. Yeah. North of Fris and the
Dialogue: 0,1:00:10.79,1:00:15.83,Default,,0,0,0,,whatchamacallit forest. And we go there.\NWe always hug the trees. You're
Dialogue: 0,1:00:15.83,1:00:20.16,Default,,0,0,0,,beautiful tree.\NThis tree was growing before Christ was
Dialogue: 0,1:00:20.16,1:00:26.31,Default,,0,0,0,,born. Every time I go there in Marin\NCounty there and you look at this
Dialogue: 0,1:00:26.31,1:00:37.44,Default,,0,0,0,,incredible tree and this tree was here a\Nthousand years before Christ was born
Dialogue: 0,1:00:37.44,1:00:43.11,Default,,0,0,0,,and therefore it's like a gift to stand\Nnext to the tree and we always hug it.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:43.11,1:00:49.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Sus and I go to uh there and we both hug\Na tree and we tell the tree how much we
Dialogue: 0,1:00:49.20,1:01:06.79,Default,,0,0,0,,love it.\NWe wait till there's nobody watching.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:06.79,1:01:13.11,Default,,0,0,0,,We kiss the tree and tell the tree how\Nmuch we love it. But the tree is 3,000
Dialogue: 0,1:01:13.11,1:01:20.55,Default,,0,0,0,,years old and uh was a thousand years\Nold at the time of the birth of Christ.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:20.55,1:01:24.96,Default,,0,0,0,,And there was trees there we we did the\Narm on and said this tree was a thousand
Dialogue: 0,1:01:24.96,1:01:30.16,Default,,0,0,0,,years old at the time of the birth of\NChrist. Wow.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:30.16,1:01:35.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So that sort of gives you humility when\Nyou look at the reality of nature and
Dialogue: 0,1:01:35.20,1:01:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,realize that that we are just an\Nexpression of this infinite nature.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:42.00,1:01:49.11,Default,,0,0,0,,But this inner capacity to discern truth\Nfrom falsehood then is an intrinsic gift
Dialogue: 0,1:01:49.11,1:01:54.88,Default,,0,0,0,,from God. And the discovery of its\Npresence then allows us to use it in a
Dialogue: 0,1:01:54.88,1:02:01.52,Default,,0,0,0,,pragmatic way that is helpful to\Nourselves and to all of uh society.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:01.52,1:02:07.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.\NOh, where are we now? We got done with
Dialogue: 0,1:02:07.68,1:02:10.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Socrates.\N10 minutes.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:10.88,1:02:17.59,Default,,0,0,0,,>> I got 10 minutes. Well, we got the next\Nslide is number two. It says that number
Dialogue: 0,1:02:17.59,1:02:24.48,Default,,0,0,0,,two.\N>> This says number two.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:24.48,1:02:30.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Relativism versus absolutism. Now, let's\Ngo to the next slide.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:30.24,1:02:35.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah, there we are. There's number two. I\Nknew there was a two someplace.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:35.52,1:02:41.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Two two.\Nrelativism versus absolutism
Dialogue: 0,1:02:41.44,1:02:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,and protagoras's dictim. Yes. All right.\NProtagoras's dictim is very much what
Dialogue: 0,1:02:46.72,1:02:52.24,Default,,0,0,0,,goes on in current society. Pagoras in\Nancient Greece, what the world worries
Dialogue: 0,1:02:52.24,1:02:55.76,Default,,0,0,0,,about now was settled thousands of years\Nago.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:55.76,1:02:59.92,Default,,0,0,0,,And by not going for traditional\Neducation
Dialogue: 0,1:02:59.92,1:03:05.04,Default,,0,0,0,,that what's happened is that the\Ninformation and the wisdom and the
Dialogue: 0,1:03:05.04,1:03:12.16,Default,,0,0,0,,genius that was uh that has existed in\Nmankind is now lost to the modern
Dialogue: 0,1:03:12.16,1:03:17.59,Default,,0,0,0,,generation. If you ask the average\Nperson what is protagoras is dictim
Dialogue: 0,1:03:17.59,1:03:25.28,Default,,0,0,0,,they'll say huh\Nthat was handled in ancient Greece 500
Dialogue: 0,1:03:25.28,1:03:31.20,Default,,0,0,0,,BC and\Nthe dictim was it's an argument which I
Dialogue: 0,1:03:31.20,1:03:36.96,Default,,0,0,0,,think appears in Plato\Nthe person says what I believe is my
Dialogue: 0,1:03:36.96,1:03:41.28,Default,,0,0,0,,reality and what you believe is your\Nreality.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:41.28,1:03:46.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, he then jumped the conclusion\Nthese are different realities
Dialogue: 0,1:03:46.79,1:03:53.83,Default,,0,0,0,,which again was of extremely egocentric\Nviewpoint that my reality is and
Dialogue: 0,1:03:53.83,1:04:00.24,Default,,0,0,0,,therefore they are of equal value.\NTherefore they're of equal value.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:00.24,1:04:06.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Uhhuh. That what to me is real is real\Nto me and what is real is real to you.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:06.88,1:04:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That would give us certain compassion\Nfor people who are marching marching
Dialogue: 0,1:04:12.00,1:04:16.79,Default,,0,0,0,,rapidly in the wrong direction from\Ntruth that they cannot discern truth
Dialogue: 0,1:04:16.79,1:04:23.03,Default,,0,0,0,,from falsehood and therefore that which\Nthey assume to be is is is so so
Dialogue: 0,1:04:23.03,1:04:29.28,Default,,0,0,0,,relativism versus absolutism.\NThe scale of consciousness is is
Dialogue: 0,1:04:29.28,1:04:33.20,Default,,0,0,0,,absolutism.\NAbsolutism
Dialogue: 0,1:04:33.20,1:04:38.48,Default,,0,0,0,,like a thermometer or a barometer. It\Njust tells you what a thing registers.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:38.48,1:04:43.83,Default,,0,0,0,,What a thing registers at. It doesn't\Nexpress an opinion. So, another thing
Dialogue: 0,1:04:43.83,1:04:48.48,Default,,0,0,0,,people don't get about our work is they\Ncan't keep thinking that it's an opinion
Dialogue: 0,1:04:48.48,1:04:52.31,Default,,0,0,0,,and they'll say, "How come you say so\Nand so?" I didn't say it. It just
Dialogue: 0,1:04:52.31,1:04:57.11,Default,,0,0,0,,calibrated as such. I don't care what it\Ncalibrates at. There's no skin off my
Dialogue: 0,1:04:57.11,1:05:02.40,Default,,0,0,0,,nose.\NWhether it's 180, 160, you know, we do
Dialogue: 0,1:05:02.40,1:05:08.64,Default,,0,0,0,,it for the intrinsic information. So to\Nuse the method that we use requires a
Dialogue: 0,1:05:08.64,1:05:13.11,Default,,0,0,0,,detached objectivity.\NThe first thing to do is find out what
Dialogue: 0,1:05:13.11,1:05:17.68,Default,,0,0,0,,is the level of truth and then worry\Nabout how you'll handle the answer
Dialogue: 0,1:05:17.68,1:05:22.00,Default,,0,0,0,,later.\NPeople go at it the other way. They use
Dialogue: 0,1:05:22.00,1:05:27.44,Default,,0,0,0,,it to try to prove a point that they're\Nholding in mind and they get very bad
Dialogue: 0,1:05:27.44,1:05:33.44,Default,,0,0,0,,results. To get good results, you have\Nto have a scientific detachment.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:33.44,1:05:38.79,Default,,0,0,0,,First I want to know what something\Ncalibrates at. Then I'll try to
Dialogue: 0,1:05:38.79,1:05:46.16,Default,,0,0,0,,understand what does that mean later and\Nif I've had some misconceptions I'll
Dialogue: 0,1:05:46.16,1:05:50.96,Default,,0,0,0,,find that out when I see what it means.\NSo the number of people statistically
Dialogue: 0,1:05:50.96,1:05:57.11,Default,,0,0,0,,who can do the test that we do all the\Ntime is relatively low in the population
Dialogue: 0,1:05:57.11,1:06:03.44,Default,,0,0,0,,at all overall. And it's because people\Nseem to be so narcissistically in
Dialogue: 0,1:06:03.44,1:06:09.52,Default,,0,0,0,,invested. They cannot take go into a\Nscientific detachment
Dialogue: 0,1:06:09.52,1:06:15.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and and just arrive at a number and then\Nworry about the number later. They they
Dialogue: 0,1:06:15.83,1:06:20.88,Default,,0,0,0,,try to influence the result. So you\Ncan't have a vested interest in what the
